a (The Builders, New York), 1918.</li><li>See Siegfried Kracauer, ‘The Hotel Lobby,” in <em>The Mass Ornament: Weimar Essays</em>, trans. and ed. Thomas Y. Levin (Cambridge: Harvard University Press, 1995), 175–6.</li><li>See Douglas Tallack, <em>New York Sights: Visualizing Old and New New York</em> (London: Berg, 2005); and Maureen Montgomery, <em>Displaying Women: Spectacles of Leisure in Edith Wharton’s New York</em>, (New York: Routledge, 1998).</li><li>See Tom Avermaete and Anne Massey, editors, <em>Hotel Lobbies and Lounges: The Architecture of Professional Hospitality</em> (London: Routledge, 2013). In this recent collection, there is almost no mention of the individual room.</li><li>Thomas Metzinger, <em>The Ego Tunnel: The Science of the Mind and the Myth of the Self</em> (New York: Basic Books, 2009), 4.</li><li>Metzinger, <em>The Ego Tunnel</em>, 1.</li></ol></div><div class="article-citation"><h6><i class="fa fa-book"></i> Cite</h6> <cite>Hugh Campbell, &#8220;Camera In Camera,&#8221; <i>Places Journal</i>, October 2020. Accessed 09 Oct 2020. &lt;<span itemprop="url">https://placesjournal.org/article/camera-in-camera-the-photography-of-abelardo-morell/</span>&gt;</cite></div></article><div class="related-articles"><h6><a href="https://placesjournal.org/explore-places/ideas" title="Explore">More in <span itemprop="about" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Thing"> <span itemprop="name">Ideas</span></span></a></h6><ul><li><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/women-architecture-and-the-politics-of-family-leave/" title="Beyond the Pritzker"><img width="525" height="350" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Levinson-women-5_525-525x350.jpg" class="lazy lazy-hidden attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /><noscript><img width="525" height="350" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Levinson-women-5_525-525x350.jpg" class="attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /></noscript></a><h5><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/women-architecture-and-the-politics-of-family-leave/" title="Beyond the Pritzker">Beyond the Pritzker</a></h5><p class="byline">Nancy Levinson</p><div class="feature-summary"><p>A call to translate the widespread awareness of gender inequality into a political campaign with concrete goals — for instance, truly progressive family leave policies.</p></div></li><li><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/the-invention-of-wessex-thomas-hardy-as-architect/" title="The Invention of Wessex"><img width="525" height="350" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/rattenbury-03-hardy-525x350.jpg" class="lazy lazy-hidden attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /><noscript><img width="525" height="350" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/rattenbury-03-hardy-525x350.jpg" class="attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /></noscript></a><h5><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/the-invention-of-wessex-thomas-hardy-as-architect/" title="The Invention of Wessex">The Invention of Wessex</a></h5><p class="byline">Kester Rattenbury</p><div class="feature-summary"><p>Rem Koolhaas, the Smithsons, Venturi and Scott Brown &#8230; and Thomas Hardy? The famed 19th-century author was also a radical architect.</p></div></li><li><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/designs-invisible-century/" title="Design’s Invisible Century"><img width="525" height="350" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/fisher-invisible-century-1_525-525x350.jpg" class="lazy lazy-hidden attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /><noscript><img width="525" height="350" src="https://placesjournal.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/fisher-invisible-century-1_525-525x350.jpg" class="attachment-explore_thumbnail size-explore_thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="" /></noscript></a><h5><a href="https://placesjournal.org/article/designs-invisible-century/" title="Design’s Invisible Century">Design’s Invisible Century</a></h5><p class="byline">Thomas Fisher</p><div class="feature-summary"><p>It’s time for designers to grapple not just with physical objects but also with the underlying processes that influence our buildings and landscapes.</p></div></li></ul></div><div class="comment--module"><p>If you would like to <a href="https://placesjournal.org/comments" title="Places Journal Comments Policy">comment</a> on this article, or anything else on Places Journal, visit our <a href="http://facebook.com/placesjournal" title="Places Journal on Facebook">Facebook</a> page or send us a message on <a href="http://twitter.com/placesjournal" title="Places Journal on Twitter">Twitter</a>.</p></div> <span itemprop="publisher" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Places Journal"></span></section><aside class="sidebar-article" role="complementary"><div class="share-widget--wrapper"><div class="share-widget"><h4>Share</h4>  <script type="text/javascript" src="//s7.addthis.com/js/300/addthis_widget.js#pubid=ra-51f9a6816f41dfb5" async></script> <script>var addthis_share =
